uk.co.strangeskies.reflection

Class ExecutableToken<O,R>

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.co.strangeskies.reflection.ExecutableToken<O,R>
  • Type Parameters:
    O - the receiver type of the executable
    R - the return type of the executable
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    MemberToken<O>

    public class ExecutableToken<O,R>
extends Object
implements MemberToken<O>

    A type safe wrapper around Executable instances, with proper handling of generic methods, and methods on generic classes.

    executable members may be created over types which mention inference variables, or even over inference variables themselves.

      • getReceiverType

        public TypeToken<O> getReceiverType()
        Description copied from interface: MemberToken
        This is the exact instance type of this member, and may be parameterized.

        For instance methods, this should be a subtype of the raw declaring class. For constructors of inner classes, or static fields of inner classes, the instance should be a subtype of the enclosing class.

        Static members and constructors of static classes have no receiver type.

        Specified by:
        getReceiverType in interface MemberToken<O>
        Returns:
        a type token over the receiver type for invocation or field access, or over void.class if the member has no receiver type

      • withReceiverType

        public <U extends O> ExecutableToken<U,? extends R> withReceiverType(TypeToken<U> type)
        Derive a new instance of ExecutableToken with the given receiver type. This will resolve any overriding Executable to determine a new return type if necessary.

        The new ExecutableToken will always have a receiver type which is as or more specific than both the current receiver type and the given type. This means that the new receiver will be assignment compatible with the given type, but if the given type contains wildcards or inference variables which are less specific that those implied by the current receiver type, new type arguments will be inferred in their place, or further bounds may be added to them.

        Specified by:
        withReceiverType in interface MemberToken<O>
        Type Parameters:
        U - The new receiver type. The raw type of this type must be a subtype of the raw type of the current receiver type.
        Parameters:
        type - The new receiver type. The raw type of this type must be a subtype of the raw type of the current receiver type.
        Returns:
        A new ExecutableToken compatible with the given receiver type.

        The new receiver type will not be effectively more specific than the intersection type of the current receiver type and the given type. That is, any type which can be assigned to both the given type and the current receiver type, will also be assignable to the new type.

      • withInferredType

        public <U> ExecutableToken<O,U> withInferredType(TypeToken<U> targetType,
                                                 TypeToken<?>... arguments)
        Derive a new ExecutableToken fulfilling two conditions.
        • Firstly, that the result be assignment compatible with the given target type.
        • Secondly, that the arguments are compatible in either a loose invocation context, or failing that, a variable arity invocation context.

        This method uses the same type inference algorithm as the Java language, and so will only fail in those cases where the Java compiler would have failed to infer a type.

        Type Parameters:
        U - The derived ExecutableToken must be assignment compatible with this type.
        Parameters:
        targetType - The derived ExecutableToken must be assignment compatible with this type.
        arguments - The derived ExecutableToken must be loose invocation compatible, or failing that variable arity compatible, with the given arguments.
        Returns:
        A new ExecutableToken compatible with the given target type and parameters, and which has more specific arguments, type arguments, and return type than the receiving ExecutableToken.

      • invoke

        public R invoke(O receiver,
                Object... arguments)
        Invoke the wrapped Executable on the given receiver and with the given parameters. The receiver will be ignored for static methods or constructors. Variable arity invocation is not attempted.

        Due to erasure of the types of the arguments, there is a limit to what type checking can be performed at runtime. For type safe invocation, wrap arguments in TypedObject instances and use an overload of invokeSafely(Object, TypedObject...) instead.

        Parameters:
        receiver - The receiving object for the invocation. This parameter will be ignored in the case of a constructor invocation or other static method invocation.
        arguments - The argument list for the invocation.
        Returns:
        The result of the invocation.

      • invoke

        public R invoke(O receiver,
                List<? extends Object> arguments)
        Invoke the wrapped Executable on the given receiver and with the given parameters. The receiver will be ignored for static methods or constructors. Variable arity invocation is not attempted.

        Due to erasure of the types of the arguments, there is a limit to what type checking can be performed at runtime. For type safe invocation, wrap arguments in TypedObject instances and use an overload of invokeSafely(Object, TypedObject...) instead.

        Parameters:
        receiver - The receiving object for the invocation. This parameter will be ignored in the case of a constructor invocation or other static method invocation.
        arguments - The argument list for the invocation.
        Returns:
        The result of the invocation.

      • invokeSafely

        public R invokeSafely(O receiver,
                      TypedObject<?>... arguments)

        As invoke(Object, Object...), but with arguments passed with their exact types, meaning full type checking can be performed at runtime. Also, here it is possible to determine whether the invocation is intended to be variable arity, and if so an attempt is made to invoke as such.

        If the expected parameter types of this executable member contain inference variables or type variable captures, an attempt will be made to satisfy their bounds according to the given argument types.

        Parameters:
        receiver - The receiving object for the invocation. This parameter will be ignored in the case of a constructor invocation or other static method invocation.
        arguments - The typed argument list for the invocation.
        Returns:
        The result of the invocation.
